## Part One: Entropy

### John Payne and the Wire Service Birth

- **John Payne**, corrupt telegraph operator at **Western Union's Cincinnati office** (early 1900s), quit after the company adopted an anti-gambling policy refusing to transmit horse race results
- Founded **Payne Telegraph Service of Cincinnati** to report race results to bookies
- Stationed employee at racetrack with hand mirror to flash winner in code to nearby building, which telegraphed results to pool halls across Cincinnati via leased wires
- Critical advantage: bookies knew results before bettors did, preventing post-race bets on horses that had already won
- Service expanded from Saratoga to the Midwest within years
- Local anti-gambling crackdowns backfired—Chicago mayor **Carter Harrison II** banned racetrack betting, causing track attendance to plummet and illegal bookmaking to flourish

> "It is my intention to witness the sport of kings without the vice of kings." — Chicago mayor Carter Harrison II

### Mont Tennes and the Chicago Mob

- 1907: violent Chicago gangster **Mont Tennes** acquired Illinois franchise for Payne's wire service, named it **General News Bureau**
- Franchise cost Tennes $300/day; he recouped it many times over from 700+ Chicago bookie joints paying half their daily receipts
- Survived six bomb attacks (July–September 1907) from rival gangsters envious of wire service profits
- Eventually squeezed Payne out; General News Bureau expanded to New Orleans and San Francisco
- 1916: **Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis** launched federal probe; **Clarence Darrow** represented Tennes, arguing Fifth Amendment (judge ruled no federal jurisdiction over local anti-gambling statutes)
- 1927: Tennes retired, issued 100 shares of stock, sold them all, died peacefully in 1941
- Bequeathed part of fortune to **Camp Honors**, character-building summer camp for wayward boys

### Moses Annenberg and the Trust

- Largest stockholder (48 shares): **Moses "Moe" Annenberg**, publisher of the *Racing Form*
- Hired **James Ragan** to run wire service; by then, scores of competitors existed
- Annenberg and Ragan expanded by buying up smaller services or driving them out

### Irving Wexler and the Price War

- **Irving Wexler** (bootlegger, owner of **Greater New York News Service**) challenged Annenberg
- Ragan started price war; Wexler sent thugs to vandalize Annenberg's New York headquarters
- Annenberg knew Wexler was tapping into General News lines—cheaper than paying employees at each track
- Annenberg delayed race results on the tapped line, phoned timely results to his own men, who placed big bets on winning horses with Wexler's subscribers (who received delayed results and didn't know horses had already won)
- Annenberg's men refunded the day's losses to Wexler's bookies, advising switch to General News Bureau
- Service (also called **"the Trust"** or **"the Wire"**) expanded coast-to-coast, to Canada, Mexico, Cuba
- 1934: Annenberg ditched partners (as Tennes had done), established rival **Nationwide News Service**; bookies told to switch carriers or else

### AT&T's Role and Legal Opinion

- General News Bureau paralleled growth of **AT&T** (Alexander Graham Bell's telephone patents expired 1894; within years, 6,000+ local companies competed; AT&T acquired/drove most out)
- Government antitrust suit settled 1913; AT&T permitted competing phone companies to connect to long-distance network; first coast-to-coast line 1915
- AT&T added to Dow Jones average; became reliable dividend stock—"favorite stock of widows and orphans"
- General News Bureau leased lines/equipment from AT&T (like today's Internet services lease cables/routers)
- AT&T in-house legal opinion (1924): "These applicants [racing wire services] must know that a majority of their customers are bound to be owners of poolrooms and bookmakers."
- AT&T included escape clause in contracts: right to cancel service if authorities judged lessee's business illegal
- AT&T officially claimed shock that gambling occurred on its network; by mid-1930s, **Moe Annenberg** was AT&T's fifth largest customer

### John Lynch vs. Annenberg

- Annenberg's takeover infuriated other General News Bureau stockholders (now owned shares in company with no customers)
- Chicago mobster **John Lynch** took Annenberg to court; attorney **Weymouth Kirkland** argued wire service was patently illegal, court had no jurisdiction (cited 1725 precedent: English judge refused to divide loot of two disputing highwaymen)
- Court accepted Kirkland's defense
- Lynch appealed to **Al Capone's** mob (Capone in prison for tax evasion); Capone had already made unsuccessful overtures to Annenberg about acquiring wire service
- Capone enforcer **Frank Nitti** told Ragan: ally with Capone mob or Annenberg dead in twenty-four hours
- Ragan refused; Annenberg fled to Miami
- Negotiations dragged for years; eventually agreed Annenberg would pay Capone's people $1 million/year in protection money while retaining ownership

### Annenberg's Exit and Continental Press

- 1939: Annenberg faced tax evasion charges; to prove reform, walked away from wire service
- Vacuum filled by **Continental Press Service**; **James Ragan** remained at helm
- Chicago mob approached Ragan again; he still refused, prepared affidavits implicating Frank Nitti in attempted murder, told FBI he'd release them if anything happened to him
- Most powerful Italian and Jewish mobsters allied in national organization cryptically called **"the Combination"**
- Combination founded rival wire service: **Trans-American Publishing and News Service**, intending to put Continental out of business

### Ben Siegel and Trans-American

- Trans-American run by **Ben Siegel** (better known as **"Bugsy"**—a name he hated), New Yorker who moved to West Coast
- Trans-American's territory included Nevada (special case: gambling legal there)
- Siegel reasoned casino bookmaking operations draw people into casinos to play other games, so charged casino bookies usual subscription price *plus a cut of income*—in some cases, *100 percent* of bookmaking income
- June 24, 1946: **James Ragan** shot at Chicago intersection (banana truck pulled up, tarpaulin lifted, two shots rang out—one mangled arm/shoulder)
- Ragan spent six weeks under police guard in hospital; someone poisoned him (mercury in Coca-Colas or catheter)
- Mob seized Continental Press after Ragan's death
- Synergy of merging Continental and Trans-American didn't escape anyone—didn't escape Los Angeles bookies, compelled to subscribe to *both* services at $150/week each
- Siegel decided Trans-American was his own business, not the Combination's
- Building **Flamingo hotel and casino** in Las Vegas; cost far exceeded projections, owed construction company $2 million
- Told Combination's "board of directors" in New York they could have Trans-American back for $2 million; board's response was cool

### Siegel's Murder

- Siegel later learned Combination called board meeting without inviting him—bad sign
- Concerned enough to track down exiled **Lucky Luciano** in Havana; Luciano (still one of most powerful men in Combination) advised Siegel to give wire service back immediately

> "Go to hell and take the rest of those bastards along with you. I'll keep the goddamn wire as long as I want." — Ben Siegel's reply to Lucky Luciano

- Rule: no board member got death sentence; Combination broke rule for first time with Siegel
- June 20, 1947: unknown gunman shot Siegel through trellis of rose arbor in Beverly Hills; fired full clip of steel-jacketed bullets from .30 caliber army carbine; four bullets hit—one passed through Siegel's right eyeball, came to rest fifteen feet away on dining room floor tile
- Half hour before murder, four toughs assembled in Flamingo lobby; at appointed time, walked to manager, announced takeover; Combination took over Siegel's wire service too

### Political Fallout and Kefauver Hearings

- Siegel's murder was costly mistake—high-profile execution in wealthy California suburb showed organized crime reached all the way to Pacific
- Tennessee senator **Carey Estes Kefauver** branded Continental Press "Public Enemy Number One"

> "In my opinion, the wire service keeps alive the illegal gambling empire which in turn bankrolls a variety of other criminal activities in America." — Senator Kefauver

- Kefauver (folksy man who liked being photographed in coonskin cap) organized **Special Committee to Investigate Organized Crime in Interstate Commerce**
- Hearings televised, ran fifteen months starting 1950; Senate committee traveled nation, subpoenaing major organized crime figures
- Many managed to be on vacation when committee hit town; many invoked Fifth Amendment
- Committee sometimes got more interesting testimony from corrupt cops and prosecutors
- Chicago police captain admitted allowing bookie joint to operate while betting fortune on sports, elections, stock market
- Louisiana police explained they didn't have heart to close illegal casinos employing underprivileged
- High point: March 1951, committee grilled powerful crime families of New York

### Frank Costello's Testimony

- Senator asked New York mobster **Frank Costello**: "How can we curb gambling in this country?"

> "Senator, if you want to cut out gambling there's just two things you need to do. Burn the stables and shoot the horses." — Frank Costello

- Kefauver demanded to know where Costello got money to buy three buildings on Wall Street; Costello said he borrowed from gamblers
- Costello started making counterfeit Kewpie dolls for carnival prizes, built gambling empire extending to Tropical Park, Miami
- Dapper Costello agreed to testify on condition face not be televised; when he spoke, TV cameras cut to carefully manicured hands
- Costello sounded ill at ease; graceful gestures (described as "hand ballet") surreally disconnected from status as major crime boss

### Longy Zwillman's Performance

- Real mastermind behind Combination: New Jersey gangster **Longy Zwillman**
- Interviewed in Washington, presented himself as legitimate businessman baffled why brought before committee
- Addressed interrogators as "sir," politely requested photographers stop using flashbulbs

> "I feel like I'm getting shot." — Longy Zwillman to Senator Kefauver

- Senators attempted to establish interconnected social network of career criminals ran wire service for bookies plus gambling, prostitution, loan-sharking, rackets throughout country
- Mobsters denied knowing each other; Zwillman admitted knowing Costello, slightly

> "In the old days, I met everybody. Every place you went, you met somebody." — Longy Zwillman

### Willie Moretti's Testimony

- Zwillman's business associate in New Jersey: **Willie Moretti** (short, just over five feet; loud; Zwillman tall, quiet)
- Moretti dressed like gangster (omnipresent diamond stickpin), great lover of women (darker their skin, better)
- Long ago contracted syphilis, never treated, entering disease's terminal stages
- At first not problem for Zwillman—business built on intimidation; not bad to have partner violent, impulsive, losing his mind
- Moretti became problem in Kefauver hearings; testified before committee, freely admitted knowing Frank Costello, knowing every other big-name mob figure in whole country ("well-charactered men" he met at racetracks)
- Described himself as professional gambler; made $25,000 betting on 1948 presidential race (picked Truman to win)
- Senators put it to Moretti: business interests were mob-infiltrated rackets

> "Everything is a racket today." — Willie Moretti

- Left stand, invited senators to come visit him at home on Jersey shore; quickly became one of first celebrities of reality TV; prolonged fifteen minutes of fame with off-the-cuff interviews to reporters

### Vito Genovese's Response

- Too much for **Vito Genovese**; from 1949 Genovese leader of **Cosa Nostra**
- Genovese spreading rumors of Moretti's mental deterioration; if Moretti mouthing off now, what would he say as rest of brain rotted away?
- Genovese called Combination meeting; decided time to kill another board member
- October 4, 1951: Moretti shot twice in forehead at his hangout, **Joe's Elbow Room** in Cliffside, New Jersey

### Kefauver's Conclusions and Impact

- Final report: Kefauver committee traced much American organized crime to age-old Sicilian criminal brotherhood, **the Mafia**
- Kefauver concluded most powerful crime figure in America was not Italian: **Longy Zwillman**, a Jew
- Kefauver hearings, all things considered, effective; through them America learned extent of organized crime, galvanized into action
- Public sentiment turned against gambling
- Senate hearings credited with defeat of proposals to legalize gambling in California, Massachusetts, Arizona, Montana
- Kefauver recommended ban on transmission of interstate gambling results; Congress quickly passed legislation
- Surprising: it *worked*—legal pressure put mob's wire service out of business
- Maybe worked because, at dawn of television age, wire service already technologically obsolescent
- After fifty years, Payne's profitable idea came to abrupt end

### Book's Preview: AT&T, the Combination, and the Formula

- Book about curious legacy of long-ago wire service
- Twelve miles southwest of West Orange, New Jersey mansion Zwillman bought with mob money, **American Telephone and Telegraph** built scientific think tank with own monopolistic riches
- 1956: young scientist pondering employer's ambivalent relationship with bookmaking devised most successful gambling system of all time


