- **Enron**, telecommunications, portfolio insurance as "overbetting" (Wilcox 2000, 2003, 2004)

### Part VII: Signal and Noise - Shannon's Legacy

- Hershberg circa 1986: 28 percent return
- **Philip Hershberg** thought of writing article on Shannons' investing success (letters, June 23 and August 28, 1986, with Shannon's papers, LOC); Betty Shannon supplied transcript
- Hershberg circa 1986: "In a way, this is close to some of the work I have done"
- Similar views from Shannon in Philip Hershberg e-mail
- Tried Kentucky Fried Chicken (Hershberg circa 1986)
- "If we try it and don't like it" (Hershberg circa 1986)
- Letter, Shannon to Dr. George A. Roberts, Nov. 5, 1978 (Shannon's papers, LOC): "is a very difficult field"
- **Warren Buffett** praised Singleton (Train 1980)
- Downloaded stock prices (Arthur Lewbel interview)
- Portfolio value on Jan. 22, 1981: computer printout in Shannon's papers, LOC (back of sheet filled with juggling machine diagrams and formulas)
- Hershberg circa 1986: "We have not, at any time in the past 30 years..."
- "I am willing to borrow on our investments if necessary" (Hershberg circa 1986)
- Check-printer company returns (Hershberg circa 1986)
- "I have personally tried to invest money" (Roll and Shiller 1992)
- Weather effect (Hirshleifer and Shumway 2001)
- Buffett 1984: "Then some business school professor" - Fred Schwed Jr.'s *Where Are the Customers' Yachts?* makes similar case; Shannon cited Schwed's 1940 book as his favorite on investing
- Returns for 1980-82 (Ziemba 2003)
- Bamberger forbidden to go into computer room (Thorp 2004-5)
- Thorp 2004-5: "How often do you have a tuna salad sandwich"
- "I had an interest list" (Thorp e-mail)
- Mizusawa scanned news; "restricted list" (Thorp 2004-5)
- 18 percent after fees (computed from data supplied by Thorp, e-mail)
- 47 percent return (Kurson 2003; Thorp e-mail)
- Turtle Trader web site: "The advantage scientists bring into the game"
- Thorp 1997 (revised 1998): 20 percent return and 6 percent standard deviation
- "To help persuade you" (Thorp 1997, revised 1998)
- Haugen 1999 (quoted in Thorp 2004-5): "pointed to me in the audience"
- Sports betting system, experiment (Thorp interview; Thorp 1997, revised 1998)
- "by far the most popular form of recreation" (hong-kongracing.com/trackside.html)
- More wagered on single races than in year's betting elsewhere (hong-kong-racing.com/trackside.html)
- $150,000 seed money (Kaplan 2003)
- Kelly formula that takes into account effect of bet on odds (Benter 1994, Kallberg and Ziemba 1994)
- Kaplan 2003: "I would have benefited by not telling anybody...I like going to the seedy girlie bars in Makati"
- Instant messages (Kaplan 2003)
- Lost $100 million by shorting NASDAQ (Kaplan 2003)
- Kaplan 2003: "When you look at how much money I have consistently made"

### Part VII: Signal and Noise - Final Reflections

- Golomb, Berlekamp, Cover et al. 2003: "Perhaps the impact Shannon and Kelly have had on finance"
- **Robert Fano** (interview): Alzheimer's symptoms
- Put in home in 1993 (Chiu, Lin, Mcferron et al. 2001)
- Tinkering with walkers, fax machines (Coughlin 2001)
- Thorp e-mail: Exponentially growing endowment for UC Irvine
- Thorp interview: "something available in the Eastern Hemisphere"
- Samuelson personal letter, June 28, 2004: Heretic born every minute
- Thomas Cover e-mail: A story with everything except an ending
- 10 percent of M.B.A. programs teach Kelly (Hakansson interview): "shameful"
- Legg Mason Value Trust 2003 annual report: "The Kelly criterion is integral"
- Quaife 1993: "should handily beat the published investment policies"
- Cover interview: "When something keeps turning up like that...there's a dark side to infinity"
- Wilmott 2001: "life, and everything in it"
- Dostoyevsky 1966: "people, not only at roulette"
- Wilcox interview: "You've heard of Kuhn's paradigm shift?"

